\begin_layout Title
Thoughts on Nematic Order in Embryonic Morphogenesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Laurent MacKay
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Causes of apparent nematic order in living tissue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Nematic order arises from neighbour-neighbour interactions between rigid
 rod-like particles, producing long range orientational order.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kemkemer2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, a mean-field approach is used to derive a distortional energy for a cellular
 orientation field that is equivalent to the classical free energy appearing
 nematic hydrodynamics equations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Evidence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In cultures of elongated cells, neighbour-neighbour interactions are to
 be expected and indeed there is often long-range orientational order in
 such cultures:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Densely-packed neural progenitor cells in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kawaguchi2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 have a degree of orientational order, which persists on the order of 10
 cell lengths.
 Based on their observations at low densities, it seems likely that the
 interaction is primarily mechanical (e.g., through hydrostatic pressure).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Similar cultures of NIH 3T3 cells show exquisite nematic ordering 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Duclos2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, where the steady-state position of +1/2 defects in circularly confined
 domains is very well predicted by passive nematic theory.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Loosely-packed melanocytes interact, primarily biochemically via their dendrites
, to produce a high degree of orientational order 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gruler1999"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Paragraph
Complication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
However, unlike in nematic phases of actual liquid crystals, cells can change
 shape quite drastically and will almost certainly do so when dividing.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Changes in density due to cell division have been suggested to enchance
 (reduce) topological defects in extensile (contractile) models of active
 nematics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Doostmohammadi2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Even within the same culture there may be regions where cells are significantly
 more elongated than others (e.g., center vs.
 tips of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

plus
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-shaped culture in Fig.
 4a in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Saw2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
I currently do not know how we could account for this variable cell shape
 within the framework of nematic hydrodynamics, but its possible that there
 is a way to do it.
 (Ask Jimmy about this).
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
An interesting microscopic/Hamiltonian-based model can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pai2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The formalism in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Kemkemer2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 would be also be good place to start for deriving one.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Section
Effects of Nematic Order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that nematic hydrodynamics are indeed at play during tissue morphogenes
is, what can be expected as a meaningful outcome of such nematic order for
 a developping organism? Two ideas come to mind:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Orientational order can guide the flow of cells.
 If a topological defect can be positioned consistently within an embryo,
 this may be a way for the organism to organise its tissue (e.g., hydra).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Accumulation of cells at topolgical defects due to local differences in
 stress/velocity.
\end_layout

