\begin_layout Subsection
Critical analysis of the link between +1/2 defects and apoptotic extrusion
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Critical-analysis-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Saw2017, it is suggested that apoptotic extrusion is induced by the high
 compressive stresses that develop at the heads of +1/2 topological defects
 in monocultures of MDCK cells.
 While their quantitative analysis is very convincing at establishing a
 correlation between high compressive stress and apoptotic extrusion, I
 have two major issues with the line of reasoning that leads them to draw
 a causal link.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Use of caspase-3 as a marker for apoptosis.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Caspase-3 acts as an executioner, shredding the cytoskeleton to allow for
 extrusion following loss of mechanical integrity.
 This causes the cell to be pushed out of the plane by its neighbours (see
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Miroshnikova2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a similar situation with less deadly results).
 Caspase-3 activation occurs around 2-8 hours (typically 5+ hours) after
 the mechanical induction of apoptosis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Maeno2006,Lee2010"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, while other caspase-independent pathways activate in tens of minutes 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Pelling2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, caspase-3 seems a poor choice of marker for tracking apoptotic cells
 prior to extrusion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Given the flow of the monolayer (see Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:nematic_flow_and_extrusion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and the timescale of the experiments, it seems likely that apoptosis can
 be initiated far from the +1/2 defect.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
A closer analysis of stress field and cellular movements do not support
 a causal relationship.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The data shown in Fig.
 3b, Extended Data Fig.
 1i, and Extended Data Fig.
 3e suggest correlations between compressive forces and extrusion.
 N.B.
 that Extended Data Fig.
 3e clearly shows that extrusion is not limited to regions of compressive
 forces, the way the data is presented in Fig.
 3b obscures such facts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
By performing visual cell tracking on the supplemental movies, the causal
 link starts to fall apart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The region with high compressive forces slowly grows in size over time (see
 green lines in Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:nematic_flow_and_extrusion"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), but it seems that the extruded cell only enters this region just prior
 to extrusion (see note 1 in this subsection).
 Also, why do none of the other cells in this region get extruded?
\end_layout

